==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: nucleoside
<hw>nucleoside</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Biochem.)</fld> <def>A type of
molecule found in all living organisms, present mostly in chemically
combined form as a component of nucleic acids, and also in smaller
amounts in free form, consisting of a pentose sugar bound to a purine or
pyrimidine base; two types of nucleoside, <stype>ribonucleoside</stype>
and <stype>deoxyribonucleoside</stype>, are present. The most common
bases present in nucleosides are adenine, cytosine, uracil, guanine, and
thymine, and to a lesser extent hypoxanthine and other bases are found.
The most common ribonucleosides composed from these bases are called
adenosine, cytidine, uridine, and guanosine. The forms esterified with
orthophosphoric at the 5-position of the pentose are called
<partof>nucleotides</partof>. The nucleotides form the monomer units
which are combined into DNA and RNA, which carry the genetic information
required for reproduction in all known organisms.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>nucleotide</ent>⟦br⟧
